essed subjects of the present.Using recent developments in postcolonial theory, the contributors challenge traditional approaches to Hispanism. The colonial situation under which these texts were composed, with all its injustices and prejudices, still lingers, and most studies have consistently avoided the connection between this colonial legacy and the situation of disenfranchised groups today. Colonialism Past and Present challenges discursive strategies that celebrate only European cultural traits, dismiss non-European cultural legacies, and solidify constructions of national projects considered natural extensions of European civilization since independence from Spain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSpanish American literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish American literaturexSocial aspects. 4aCultural Studies : Language and Culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBolanos, Alvaro Felix, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBolaños, Alvaro Félix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastro-Klarén, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiggins, Antony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLagos, Cora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazzotti, José Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeléndez, Mariselle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabasa, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRestrepo, Luis Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlau, Stacey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerdesio, Gustavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo